--Word--|drawn |--Type--|verb, adjective|--Meanings--|(of a person) looking strained from illness, exhaustion, anxiety, or pain.|--Examples--|Cathy was pale and drawn and she looked tired out|
--Word--|freshness |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|(with reference to food) the state of being recently made or obtained or not having decayed.|The quality of being pleasantly new or different.|The state of being recently created or experienced and not faded or impaired.|The quality of being attractively youthful and unspoilt.|Energy and vigour.|Brightness or healthiness of complexion or appearance.|(with reference to wind) the quality of being cool and fairly strong.|The quality of being pleasantly clean and cool.|--Examples--|the restaurant's selling point is the freshness of its ingredients|he brings freshness to a familiar story|the commentary should display freshness of insight|the freshness of the memory|he has the enthusiasm and freshness of youth|his freshness, passion, and focus got him cast in leading roles|she has retained the freshness of face that was there at her debut|the frescoes still retain their freshness and colour|the freshness of the wind with its cooling air|the minty freshness of toothpaste|
--Word--|freshen |--Type--|verb|--Meanings--|Make (something) newer, cleaner, or more attractive.|Add more liquid to (a drink); top up.|(of wind) become stronger and colder.|(of a cow) give birth and come into milk.|freshen up|Refresh oneself by washing or changing into clean clothes.|freshen something up|Make something look newer or more attractive.|--Examples--|it didn't take long to freshen her make-up|the waitress freshened their coffee|the westerly wind freshened and howled dismally|the yachts picked up a freshening breeze|he went off to freshen up in the local baths|you can freshen up a tired sofa by draping it with interesting fabric|

--Word--|freshener |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|A substance or device that makes something fresher or cleaner.|A quantity of a drink that refills a partly full glass or cup; a top-up.|--Examples--|parsley is a natural breath freshener|chemicals that smell like toilet freshener|yes, thank you, I will take a freshener|

--Word--|Wöhler, Friedrich |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(1800–82), German chemist. His synthesis of urea from ammonium cyanate in 1828 demonstrated that organic compounds could be made from inorganic compounds. He was also the first to isolate the elements aluminium and beryllium.|--Examples--|
--Word--|friend |--Type--|noun, verb|--Meanings--|A person with whom one has a bond of mutual affection, typically one exclusive of sexual or family relations.|(used as a polite form of address or in ironic reference) an acquaintance or a stranger one comes across.|One's close relatives.|A person who supports a cause, organization, or country by giving financial or other help.|A person who is not an enemy or opponent; an ally.|A familiar or helpful thing.|A contact on a social networking website.|A member of the Religious Society of Friends; a Quaker.|Add (someone) to a list of friends or contacts on a social networking website.|Befriend (someone).|Have a sexual relationship with.|--Examples--|she's a friend of mine|we were close friends|my friends, let me introduce myself|the Friends of the Welsh National Opera|she was unsure whether he was friend or foe|he settled for that old friend the compensation grant|all of a sudden you've got 50 friends online who need to stay connected|I am friended by 29 people who I have not friended back|the woman got married and you still used to friend with she?|

--Word--|friendly |--Type--|adjective, noun|--Meanings--|Kind and pleasant.|(of a person) on good or affectionate terms.|(of relations) not in conflict.|Not seriously or unpleasantly competitive or divisive.|(of a game or match) not forming part of a serious competition.|Denoting something that is adapted for or is not harmful to a specified thing.|Favourable or serviceable.|(of troops or equipment) of, belonging to, or allied with one's own forces.|A game or match that does not form part of a serious competition.|--Examples--|they were friendly to me|she gave me a friendly smile|I was friendly with one of the local farmers|we want friendly relations with all countries|friendly rivalry between the two schools|an environment-friendly agronomic practice|child-friendly policies|no one noticed her as she slipped out—it was a friendly night|the risk of blowing up friendly forces is minimized|England will play two friendlies in Sardinia|

--Word--|front |--Type--|noun, adjective, verb|--Meanings--|The side or part of an object that presents itself to view or that is normally seen or used first; the most forward part of something.|The position directly ahead of someone or something; the most forward position or place.|The forward-facing part of a person's body, on the opposite side to their back.|The part of a garment covering a person's front.|A woman's bust or cleavage.|Any face of a building, especially that of the main entrance.|The foremost line or part of an armed force; the furthest position that an army has reached and where the enemy is or may be engaged.|The direction towards which a line of troops faces when formed.|A particular formation of troops for battle.|A particular situation or sphere of operation.|An organized political group.|The forward edge of an advancing mass of air.|An appearance or form of behaviour assumed by a person to conceal their genuine feelings.|A person or organization serving as a cover for subversive or illegal activities.|Boldness and confidence of manner.|A person's face or forehead.|Of or at the front.|(of a vowel sound) formed by raising the tongue, excluding the blade and tip, towards the hard palate.|(of a building or piece of land) have the front facing or directed towards.|Be or stand in front of.|Provide (something) with a front or facing of a particular type or material.|Lead or be the most prominent member in (an organization, group, or activity)|Present or host (a television or radio programme)|Act as a front or cover for illegal or secret activity.|Adopt a particular expression or form of behaviour to conceal one's genuine feelings.|Make an appearance; turn up.|Stand face to face with; confront.|Articulate (a vowel sound) with the tongue further forward.|Place (a sentence element) at the beginning of a sentence instead of in its usual position, typically for emphasis or as a feature of some dialects, as in horrible it was.|--Examples--|a page at the front of the book had been torn out|he sealed the envelope and wrote on the front|she quickly turned her head to face the front|she rolled over on to her front|porridge slopped from the tray on to his shirt front|get your eyes off my front, meathead|the west front of the Cathedral|his regiment was immediately sent to the front|the Spartans preserving an even and unbroken front|there was some good news on the jobs front|the National Progressive Patriotic Front|she put on a brave front|the CIA identified the company as a front for a terrorist group|he's got a bit of talent and a lot of front|the mark of fool set on his front|the front cover of the magazine|she was in the front garden|the flats which fronted Crow Road|both properties fronted on to the beach|they reached the hedge fronting the garden|a metal box fronted by an alloy panel|a glass-fronted bookcase|the group is fronted by two girl singers|she is set to front a new BBC show|he fronted for them in illegal property deals|I can't front, I never really listened to much of his music|parents get a bit worried if you don't front up now and then|Tom fronted him with unwavering eyes|the three velar consonants are normally fronted to some degree|the fronting of /au/ was completed a couple of generations ago|

--Word--|Fulbright, William |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(1905–95), American senator; full name James William Fulbright. His name designates grants awarded under the Fulbright Act of 1946, which authorized funds from the sale of surplus war materials overseas to be used to finance exchange programmes of students and teachers between the US and other countries. The scheme was later supported by grants from the US government.|--Examples--|

--Word--|functionalism |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|The theory that the design of an object should be determined by its function rather than by aesthetic considerations, and that anything practically designed will be inherently beautiful.|The theory that all aspects of a society serve a function and are necessary for the survival of that society.|(in the philosophy of mind) the theory that mental states can be sufficiently defined by their cause, their effect on other mental states, and their effect on behaviour.|--Examples--|

--Word--|furrowed |--Type--|adjective|--Meanings--|(of land or earth) covered in long, narrow trenches formed by ploughing.|(of the forehead or face) marked with lines or wrinkles.|--Examples--|furrowed fields|he stroked his furrowed brow|
--Word--|furrow |--Type--|noun, verb|--Meanings--|A long, narrow trench made in the ground by a plough, especially for planting seeds or irrigation.|A rut, groove, or trail in the ground or another surface.|A line or wrinkle on a person's face.|Make a rut, groove, or trail in (the ground or the surface of something)|Use a plough to make a long, narrow trench in (land or earth)|(with reference to the forehead or face) mark or be marked with lines or wrinkles caused by frowning, anxiety, or concentration.|--Examples--|regular furrows in a ploughed field|fields of ridge and furrow|lorry wheels had dug furrows in the sand|there were deep furrows in his brow|gorges furrowing the deep-sea floor|John's face was furrowed with tears|the tractors continuously furrowed the fields for several days|a look of concern furrowed his brow|his brows furrowed in concentration|

--Word--|fuse |--Type--|verb, noun, noun, verb|--Meanings--|Join or blend to form a single entity.|(of groups of atoms or cellular structures) join or coalesce.|Melt (a material or object) with intense heat so as to join it with something else.|(of an electrical appliance) stop working when a fuse melts.|Cause (an electrical appliance) to stop working when a fuse melts.|Provide (a circuit or electrical appliance) with a fuse.|A safety device consisting of a strip of wire that melts and breaks an electric circuit if the current exceeds a safe level.|A length of material along which a small flame moves to explode a bomb or firework, meanwhile allowing time for those who light it to move to a safe distance.|A device in a bomb that controls the timing of the explosion.|Fit a fuse to (a bomb, shell, or mine)|--Examples--|intermarriage had fused the families into a large unit|the two nuclei move together and fuse into one nucleus|attempts to fuse nuclei together|powdered glass was fused to a metal base|when fired in a special kiln, the metals fused on to the pot|the crew were left in darkness after the lights fused|he will fuse the entire lighting system of the camp|there is no need to fuse the circuit any higher unless there is other equipment on the same circuit|a bomb on a short fuse|the bomb was fused to go off during a charity performance|

--Word--|futurism |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Concern with events and trends of the future, or which anticipate the future.|An artistic movement begun in Italy in 1909, which strongly rejected traditional forms and embraced the energy and dynamism of modern technology. Launched by Filippo Marinetti, it had effectively ended by 1918 but was widely influential, particularly in Russia on figures such as Malevich and Mayakovsky.|--Examples--|
--Word--|futurism |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Concern with events and trends of the future, or which anticipate the future.|An artistic movement begun in Italy in 1909, which strongly rejected traditional forms and embraced the energy and dynamism of modern technology. Launched by Filippo Marinetti, it had effectively ended by 1918 but was widely influential, particularly in Russia on figures such as Malevich and Mayakovsky.|--Examples--|
--Word--|futurist |--Type--|noun, adjective|--Meanings--|An adherent of Futurism.|A person who studies the future and makes predictions about it based on current trends.|A person who believes that eschatological prophecies are still to be fulfilled.|Relating to Futurism or the Futurists.|Relating to a vision of the future.|--Examples--|the agency hired a futurist to pinpoint trends|the Futurist painters|the grim urban setting of the novel would have been a futurist nightmare|

--Word--|fuse |--Type--|verb, noun, noun, verb|--Meanings--|Join or blend to form a single entity.|(of groups of atoms or cellular structures) join or coalesce.|Melt (a material or object) with intense heat so as to join it with something else.|(of an electrical appliance) stop working when a fuse melts.|Cause (an electrical appliance) to stop working when a fuse melts.|Provide (a circuit or electrical appliance) with a fuse.|A safety device consisting of a strip of wire that melts and breaks an electric circuit if the current exceeds a safe level.|A length of material along which a small flame moves to explode a bomb or firework, meanwhile allowing time for those who light it to move to a safe distance.|A device in a bomb that controls the timing of the explosion.|Fit a fuse to (a bomb, shell, or mine)|--Examples--|intermarriage had fused the families into a large unit|the two nuclei move together and fuse into one nucleus|attempts to fuse nuclei together|powdered glass was fused to a metal base|when fired in a special kiln, the metals fused on to the pot|the crew were left in darkness after the lights fused|he will fuse the entire lighting system of the camp|there is no need to fuse the circuit any higher unless there is other equipment on the same circuit|a bomb on a short fuse|the bomb was fused to go off during a charity performance|

--Word--|fuzzy |--Type--|adjective|--Meanings--|Having a frizzy texture or appearance.|Difficult to perceive; indistinct or vague.|(of a person or the mind) unable to think clearly; confused.|(of popular music or electric instruments) having or producing a distorted buzzing tone; fuzzed.|Relating to a form of set theory and logic in which predicates may have degrees of applicability, rather than simply being true or false. It has important uses in artificial intelligence and the design of control systems.|--Examples--|fuzzy fake-fur throw pillows|the picture is very fuzzy|that fuzzy line between right and wrong|my mind felt fuzzy|their former jolly sound has been drowned in swathes of layered, fuzzy guitar|
